node.text:
@rosehoneyp & I went grocery shopping to show you some better options for feeding your kids and family. 

1. Look for jams/jelly that are low in sugar, no more than 5 grams per serving. I like the 2 brands I showed bc they sweeten with fruit juice concentrate, not cane sugar. Organic is a must, bc berries are always at the top of the dirty dozen.

2. Look for gluten pasta made from nutrient dense lentils, chickpeas, or brown rice. I don't think gluten is good for anyone, especially kids, and enriched wheat macaroni has ZERO nutrition. 

3. Avoid juices from the middle aisles, they are high heat pasteurized and basically sugar water. Look for cold pressed juices in the middle aisles, they have fruit and veggies blends that are great options for kids.

node.text:
@rosehoneyp & I went grocery shopping to show you some better options for feeding your kids and family. 

1. Look for jams/jelly that are low in sugar, no more than 5 grams per serving. I like the 2 brands I showed bc they sweeten with fruit juice concentrate, not cane sugar. Organic is a must, bc berries are always at the top of the dirty dozen.

2. Look for gluten pasta made from nutrient dense lentils, chickpeas, or brown rice. I don't think gluten is good for anyone, especially kids, and enriched wheat macaroni has ZERO nutrition. 

3. Avoid juices from the middle aisles, they are high heat pasteurized and basically sugar water. Look for cold pressed juices in the middle aisles, they have fruit and veggies blends that are great options for kids.
